# FANUC Safety Rule

Every motion-touching artifact is a safety artifact. This rule applies whenever you are authoring a TP/KAREL program, a safety review, or a DCS configuration document.

## Standards baseline

- ISO 10218-1:2011 - manufacturer requirements for industrial robots.
- ISO 10218-2:2011 - integrator / system requirements.
- ISO/TS 15066:2016 - collaborative operations; body-region power/force limits.
- ANSI/RIA R15.06-2012 - US harmonization.
- FANUC DCS Operator's Manual - controller-specific safe functions.

Canon entries: `fanuc_dataset/normalized/safety/ONE_iso10218_overview.md`, `ONE_iso_ts_15066_basics.md`, `FANUC_SAFE_DCS_*.md`. Cite by ID.

## FANUC DCS coverage

When specifying or reviewing a FANUC installation, DCS is non-optional if any of the following are true:

- Operator can reach into the workcell envelope during production.
- Collaborative (CR/CRX) variant.
- Multi-robot cell where one robot can reach another's envelope.
- Reduced-speed zones for teach vs auto.

Functions to specify explicitly:

- Joint Position Check (JPC) - per-axis limits.
- Joint Speed Check (JSC) - per-axis speed limits.
- Cartesian Position Check (CPC) - TCP-in-zone check.
- Cartesian Speed Check (CSC) - TCP speed limit.
- Tool Frame (TF) - DCS-validated tool geometry.
- User Frame (UF) - DCS-validated base.
- Safe I/O - Category-rated inputs/outputs (SI/SO).

Every zone and limit gets an entry in the safety review:

```markdown
| ID | Type | Purpose | Coordinates / limit | Stop category | Tested |
|----|------|---------|---------------------|---------------|--------|
| CPC1 | Cartesian Position Check | Exclude operator station | XYZ box [...] | Cat. 1 | YYYY-MM-DD |
```

## Collaborative (CR / CRX) additional discipline

- Identify the collaborative mode(s): Safety-rated monitored stop (SRMS), hand-guide (HG), speed/separation monitoring (SSM), power/force limiting (PFL).
- PFL analyses cite ISO/TS 15066 body region tables; compute transient and quasi-static limits.
- Document cycle-time penalty so the customer isn't surprised.

## E-stop and fault recovery

- E-stop is category 1 by default on R-30iB; confirm for the specific controller.
- Software interrupts (`MONITOR`) are NOT safety functions. They do not substitute for DCS.
- Fault recovery path is specified; "press FAULT_RESET" is not a recovery plan.

## Motion that fails review

- Unbounded WAIT without fault escalation.
- Speed > DCS cartesian speed limit.
- Motion that enters a Safe Position Check zone without an explicit justification + override analysis.
- CR/CRX motion without PFL analysis cited.
- Programmatic `$OVERRIDE` modification.
- Tool frames set at runtime from uncontrolled sources.

## What the Safety agent produces

`SAFETY_REVIEW_*.md` using `cowork/templates/SAFETY_REVIEW_TEMPLATE.md` and validated against `cowork/schemas/safety_review.schema.json`. Record goes under `task_state.safety`.

## Escalation

Any finding graded `severity: critical` halts the workflow until the human sign off is recorded in `task_state.safety.signoff`. No exceptions.
